entry.title: Fix unnecessary AX tree traversals to prevent freezing on certain HTML
entry.content:
Previously, GetSpellingAndGrammarAttributes() looped through all

the text children of a native text field to find the spelling/grammar

information we needed to expose to assistive tech. However, we didn't

check that the text field was nonempty to start with. If it's an empty

text field, NextTextOnlyObject() will not find a descendant text node

but instead return a text node outside the text field, which can start

unnecessary tree traversals.



Now, we will only execute the above logic if the text field is nonempty.

This should guarantee that our loop traverses among only descendants

of the text field.

entry.title: [WebAuthn][CredMan] Index WebAuthnCredManDelegate by frame
entry.content:
Currently WebAuthnCredManDelegate is attached to a WebContents by

way of its UserData.



This is a problem because it is possible for multiple frames within a

single WebContents to be invoking conditional UI. This means callbacks

from the conditional requests in each frame could contend with each

other, and also a tap on a username field that activates the

conditional request could end up triggering a request associated with

the wrong frame.



This change adds a factory class that creates WebAuthnCredManDelegate

instances. The factory is WebContents bound but internally it keeps

a map of frames to delegate instances.

entry.title: Prevent WebView crashes inside GetCookieDomainWithString()
entry.content:
This DCHECK is being hit by WebView clients whenever they create a

cookie without the `Domain` attribute using a url with an empty leading

label. E.x.: https://.example.com



While the cookie code should eventually be modified to support empty

leading labels, this bug shouldn't be causing any noticeable issues

for the WebView clients at the moment.



So in the meantime the DCHECK will be changed to a DUMP_WILL_BE_CHECK

to allow us to continue to collect usage data and show that this will,

eventually, be an invariant.

entry.title: Reland "Extend period identified as printing content analysis"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 044be5b5ac3c050fb14713f634a22cb5de5171f2



Wrapped analyzing_content_ variable and access method with the

ENABLE_PRINT_CONTENT_ANALYSIS build flag.



Original change's description:

> Extend period identified as printing content analysis

>

> PrintViewManagerBase and PrintViewManager use a state variable to know

> when the document is being checked for content analysis. This state

> has been set only around the time when a snapshot is being collected,

> but has not been including the time for the actual composition and

> analysis. This interfered with the out-of-process print drivers

> feature logic, resulting in crashes when both features are being used

> because a Print Backend service client would unregister prematurely.

>

> Modify the content analysis state to track the entire time that the

> document is being checked, resetting it only once an accept/reject

> decision has been made. Update the name of this state variable to

> better reflect this new approach. This allows PrintViewManagerBase to

> check the state in some extra places and ensure that Print Backend

> client registration persists while content analysis is still in

> progress.

>

> Also add some extra detail to the logging statement in

> PrintBackendServiceManager::RegisterClient(), which was helpful to

> understand how this problem was occurring.

>

> This allows content analysis browser tests to now complete the printing

> sequence without crashing for both in-browser and OOPPD configurations.

>

> Fixed: 1450620

entry.title: [heap] Distinguish between roots and reference to root in gc plugin
entry.content:
The blink gc plugin is checking for roots in GCed classes. It currently

reports Persistent* and Persistent& as roots. Since the class is not

keeping these roots alive, the current error message is misleading.

Since fileds of type Persistent* and Persistent& should not be needed,

we still want to prohibit them.

Adjust the error message accordingly.

entry.title: CrOS Settings: Separating first and subsequent lifetime metrics.
entry.content:
Separating "ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime"

into ".FirstWeek" and ".SubsequentWeeks". Assuming that users will change more Settings in the first week to customize their device to their liking, so to understand the data better, we will separate the data into 2 histograms. This will help us understand the true value of how many Settings users will change on average, without the data from the first week skewing the results.



This CL is a follow-up to b/280480850.



BUG=b/281946097

TEST=

Manual:

A)

1. Run ChromeOS with OOBE. Take the onboarding steps.

2. Open Settings.

2. Change a Setting that we are recording the name of, such as

switching the toggle for Do Not Disturb.

3. Close the Settings app, open your browser and search

"chrome://histograms", then find the histogram

"ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime.FirstWeek". There

will be one count added to the respective bucket. The bucket

represents the number of unique changes made over the device's

lifetime.

4. Repeat steps 1-3 with different Settings changed each time. The

histogram will each time record the correct number of accumulated

unique Settings changed.

B)

1. Repeat 'A' after a week time has passed.

2. The corresponding histogram will now be called

"ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime.SunsequentWeeks"

NOTE: The recorded count has now been reset, meaning that if we repeat `Do not disturb` toggle

flip after the first week, we will now record it again in

histogram ".SubsequentWeeks".

3. No data will be added to ".FirstWeek" after the first week has

passed.



--gtest_filter="*SettingsUserActionTrackerTest*"



Unittest: DISPLAY=:20 out/Default/unit_tests

entry.title: fix payloadRef not found failure due to app crashes
entry.content:
XC15 added a video recording feature on failed tests. However, when app crashes happen, the video file attachments don't exist, but the file name still show up in test results, causing test runner unable to find the file payloadRef. Therefore, we should skip copying attachments when their payloadRef doesn't exist.
